00:13:13.739 --> 00:13:21.739
So there are ways to get a conversion from LaTeX to types that you can use Pandoc.

00:13:21.739 --> 00:13:24.460
For Pandoc is a tool that we use inside Corto.

00:13:24.460 --> 00:13:28.979
You can access Pandoc from, if you have an installation of Corto, you automatically have

00:13:28.979 --> 00:13:31.140
also an installation of Pandoc.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:38.020
And Pandoc allows you to do conversions from LaTeX into types, which Corto doesn't do.

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:42.739
Corto focuses on starting with either Jupyter documents, Jupyter notebooks, and Markdown,

00:13:42.739 --> 00:13:45.580
and then producing a variety of different outputs.

00:13:45.580 --> 00:13:49.219
But Pandoc does something a little more generic with respect to documents.

00:13:49.219 --> 00:13:53.299
You can give it LaTeX as input, and it will try to convert to types.

00:13:53.299 --> 00:13:54.299
So you can do this.

00:13:54.299 --> 00:13:58.140
It requires a little bit of work on the command line to find where Pandoc is and give it the

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:01.179
LaTeX document, and then get the types document out.

00:14:01.179 --> 00:14:04.580
But if you need a place to get started, that would be the way to do it.

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:09.500
And if my answer is not enough to get you unblocked, again, please reach out to us over

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:13.460
email, and we'll be happy to help you sort that out.

