00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:45.140
A question a bit...

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:48.260
I think this one was from the registration, actually.

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:56.299
What are the disadvantages of types relative to other PDF formatters in Cordo?

00:14:56.299 --> 00:14:59.020
That's a great question.

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:02.500
Types is a very new typesetting system.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:07.140
So it has existed for about a year and a half now, I think, publicly.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:08.140
Maybe a little bit more.

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:10.099
But it's quite new.

00:15:10.099 --> 00:15:15.859
And what that means is that there's much less of a developed ecosystem around it.

00:15:15.859 --> 00:15:23.700
So if you want to use something like PDF LaTeX, there's literally 40 years of folks using

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:27.219
LaTeX in one way or another that you get to benefit from.

00:15:27.219 --> 00:15:29.619
And in types, you don't get that.

00:15:29.619 --> 00:15:31.820
The community is very fast growing.

00:15:31.820 --> 00:15:36.940
I'm always surprised by the excitement that folks have around types.

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:37.940
And me too.

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:46.580
I really enjoy using types, and I hope that eventually we can put LaTeX to rest.

00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:49.099
It is a fantastic system, but it shows its age.

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:54.299
So I'd love to support types better, and getting community support and an ecosystem around

00:15:54.299 --> 00:15:55.299
it is a big part of it.

00:15:55.299 --> 00:16:02.140
But that's the main thing you're going to miss, is sort of the very long tail of strange

00:16:02.140 --> 00:16:04.380
packages that do absolutely everything you need.

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:06.580
That does not exist in types so much.

00:16:06.580 --> 00:16:07.580
But it will.

00:16:07.580 --> 00:16:13.179
It's already a lot better than it was even six months ago.

00:16:13.179 --> 00:16:19.020
I see you were answering this one in the YouTube chat as well, but we can cover it here too.

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:24.219
Samantha asks, are there ways to customize how types renders or essentially add partials

00:16:24.219 --> 00:16:27.140
like when using LaTeX in Cordo?

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:32.659
Yeah, we have a general mechanism that exists not only for types, but for other systems,

00:16:32.659 --> 00:16:35.619
for other formats as well.

00:16:35.619 --> 00:16:38.500
So Samantha mentioned partials.

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:42.539
This is the way to sort of change little bits of the document and give it a new template.

00:16:42.539 --> 00:16:45.340
The same system exists for types.

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:50.179
We shared a link to the documentation that talks about custom formats in types to do

00:16:50.179 --> 00:16:51.179
that.

00:16:51.179 --> 00:16:56.780
So that's all available, just in the same way.

00:16:56.780 --> 00:16:58.380
I'm not saying anything wrong, right, Gordon?

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:00.140
Just checking with the actual types expert.

00:17:00.140 --> 00:17:05.020
But I'm almost certain that's exactly how it works.

00:17:05.020 --> 00:17:09.739
Gordon, anything you want to add?

00:17:09.739 --> 00:17:12.739
There was a slight small thing on the last question.

00:17:12.739 --> 00:17:17.459
One of the limitations of types in Cordo is we don't yet have books support.

00:17:17.459 --> 00:17:20.540
We would definitely like to have that.

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:21.540
That's a great point.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:26.699
So if you're using LaTeX, if you're using the other PDF format, you get a textbook.

00:17:26.699 --> 00:17:30.739
So if you want to go down the route, we use PDF LaTeX and we can't currently do it in

00:17:30.739 --> 00:17:31.739
types.

00:17:31.739 --> 00:17:37.140
We'll fix that, but it's currently not available.

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:42.339
I realized this was actually a different question than what we had asked earlier, but Sean had

00:17:42.339 --> 00:17:51.780
asked, if you generate multiple Cordo docs, can you deploy them all at once in PositConnect?

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:53.160
You probably could.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:55.859
So there is an R package for deploying things that connect.

00:17:55.859 --> 00:18:02.900
So there's no reason to think you can't iteratively have some kind of loop or purr to render them

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:04.180
all to connect.

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:08.859
That probably wouldn't be my recommendation because you wouldn't want to kind of bulk

00:18:08.859 --> 00:18:16.420
deploy 200 plus PDFs to connect, because it then becomes 200 now pieces of content

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:18.939
you have to manage on the Connect server.

00:18:18.939 --> 00:18:22.819
So I would, I think this is, you know, I've tried to present it as a use case where you

00:18:22.819 --> 00:18:27.900
just have one template and then it gives kind of users of that template to generate whatever

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:29.099
document they want.

00:18:29.099 --> 00:18:34.300
But again, if you really wanted to, you probably could, and you can check out the RS Connect

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:40.780
package in R for programmatically deploying to connect.

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:41.780
Thank you.

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:46.859
I'll try and go grab the link to that package right after this one too.

