00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:10.719
A types question that came in was, how well does types work for citations?

00:22:10.719 --> 00:22:14.199
This is a new word for me.

00:22:14.199 --> 00:22:15.199
Zotero integration.

00:22:15.199 --> 00:22:17.800
Zotero is a bibliography manager.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:21.880
So folks who work in academia and need to know about their 500 papers that they have

00:22:21.880 --> 00:22:27.199
to cite regularly, they have a separate program for folks that don't know it.

00:22:27.199 --> 00:22:32.839
So Quarto has Zotero integration through RStudio and its VS code integration.

00:22:32.839 --> 00:22:37.599
So you can use the visual editor and sort of automatically bring references from your

00:22:37.599 --> 00:22:39.640
own Zotero library.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:42.359
And types will work with that.

00:22:42.359 --> 00:22:46.520
So types needs its own sort of library for doing this.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:51.640
But you can use Quarto to pull in your citations from your Zotero library, and then we will

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:54.119
render them using types.

00:22:54.119 --> 00:22:59.839
And the latest version of types supports the citation style language, which is this standard

00:22:59.839 --> 00:23:04.479
for figuring out all the different ways in which citations and references are generated,

00:23:04.479 --> 00:23:07.520
like from Chicago to APA and sort of all of this.

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:12.079
So for academic folks, that's essentially what you need, because then you just find

00:23:12.079 --> 00:23:15.839
the file that describes the citation style for your journal or for something like that,

00:23:15.839 --> 00:23:17.199
and you can just use it.

00:23:17.199 --> 00:23:23.760
So it actually has really solid support for citations and bibliography management, about

00:23:23.760 --> 00:23:29.479
as good as PDF LaTeX.

00:23:29.479 --> 00:23:31.160
Thank you.

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:36.760
This is a question from the registration, and I know, Ryan, you showed this a bit in

00:23:36.760 --> 00:23:40.560
the demo, but I just wanted to reiterate, someone said, I'd like to have a download

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:45.280
button on the Quarto website or Shiny app where these reports can be directly printed

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:46.280
by the users.

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:47.280
Yeah.

00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:52.680
During the demo, we kind of, again, it was not a very flashy Shiny application, but it

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:55.959
had a button right there that said Download Report.

00:23:55.959 --> 00:24:01.239
So they can download via that document or the poster version.

00:24:01.239 --> 00:24:06.520
So totally doable within Shiny application, within a Quarto website, I don't know if it's

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:15.160
possible to have like an interactive download button, but I think you can, right?

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:21.119
So the main constraint there is in a Quarto website, you typically don't have a Shiny

00:24:21.119 --> 00:24:23.719
dashboard integrated on the website, right?

00:24:23.719 --> 00:24:28.599
So you could have to have the Shiny application running on an R server somewhere.

00:24:28.599 --> 00:24:30.599
There are ways around it.

00:24:30.599 --> 00:24:35.599
So if you, so there are Quarto extensions that George Stagg has developed, they're called

00:24:35.599 --> 00:24:41.359
Shiny Live, which George and Barrett have developed, which do all of the R work, but

00:24:41.359 --> 00:24:45.280
they work in WebAssembly, if you've heard this, which is sort of running your R code like

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:48.160
on the browser rather than somewhere.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:53.040
And then you can pretend that you're running a full Shiny dashboard that's interactive,

00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:55.479
but it's actually running right on your browser.

00:24:55.479 --> 00:24:59.839
And so that could be integrated in a Quarto website, which then could have the link to

00:24:59.839 --> 00:25:02.719
something that generates the PDF file.

00:25:02.719 --> 00:25:07.040
This is something that we really need to give you examples so we can build off of, and we

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:09.680
don't have a great example of that today.

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:11.000
We're working on that.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.439
And so for like early next year, look out for sort of like a more substantive set of

00:25:16.439 --> 00:25:19.680
these harder use cases, but it should be possible.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:24.280
So it just takes connecting the right bits together in a slightly different way than

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:25.839
you would think of to do.

